          <p>Welcome Back!</p>
          
          <p>We are getting closer to running your game. </p>
      
          <p>This time please do the following:</p>
          <p>Click on File.</p>
           <p>Click on Build Settings (not Build and Run, we are not ready for that just yet).</p>
           <p>Build Settings should then pop up. You should see on the left hand side
           an area called Platform.</p>
           <p>This area is where we decide what we want our game to run on. You should see that 
           PC, Mac, & Linux Standalone, as well as Android have items on the right hand side. If you click on
           PS4 or iOS, they should only have a message asking for you to download their module.
           That is because we have only downloaded the Android version and the PC version is default.</p>
           
           <p>If you do not already have the Build Settings on the Android Platform, please do so now.</p>
          <p>Click on Android and at the bottom of the information for Android, click on the button that says
          Switch Platform. </p>
          
          <p>If you have not yet done so, make sure your current scene is checked in the box above the platform information.
          If you have not done this yet, follow the next step. if you have done this, continue on.</p>
          <p>Still in <b>Build Settings</b> click on the <b>Add Open Scenes</b> button. It will be the
              button right underneath a large empty space. When you do that, you should see:
              <strong>Scenes/SampleScene</strong> pop up. </p>
              
          <p><b>SampleScene</b> is currently the name of our scene and <b>Scenes</b> is folder where all of our
              scenes are being stored in. A scene holds all of the objects, materials, and information regarding 
              a specific part of a game. If you ever play video games and the game reloads for a moment to take you to a 
              new location in a game, that is an example of the game changing and loading a new scene.</p>
  
          
          <p>When that is done, click Build and Run. It will now ask you for a file name. Save this file as 
          MyFirstGameTestComputer.</p>
          <p>Click on Save.</p>
          
          <p>Now let's wait for it to run. You should get an error saying there is no Android Device plugged in.</p>
          <p>As long as that is your only error in this step, then you are good. We do not want to plug anything in just yet. </p>
          
          
          <p>If not and you get an error saying <strong>Android JDk/SDK</strong> is not working, then do the following.</p>
          
          
          <p>Close your project. Open <b>Unity Hub</b>. Click on <b>Installs</b>. Click on the three dotes next to version of Unity you are currently using. 
          Click on <b>Add Modules</b>. Click on the arrow tab next to <b>Android Build Support</b> and click on:</p>
          
          <li>Android SDK & NDK Tools</li>
          <li>OpenJDK</li>
          
          <p>When all of this is clicked, click on <b>Done</b>.</p>
          <p>These items should now be installing. When they are done, open up your project and try to <b>Build and Run</b>.</p>
          
          <p>If everything works, you should get a 'No Android Device detected'.</p>
          
          <p>If you are still receiving errors, please go to the <a href="help4">Help</a> page for further assistance.</p>
         
          
          
          <p>Great! Everything should be working. Go onto the next tutorial for the next step. </p>

